---

👉 In Agile (Scrum, XP, etc.), you should not directly correlate story points with man-days.
Story points are not a measure of time, but a measure of relative effort that takes into account:

the complexity of the work,

the amount of work,

and the uncertainty or risk involved.



---

🧭 Why you shouldn’t convert directly

Story points are used to compare stories to each other (e.g., an 8-point story is roughly twice as big as a 4-point one).

Man-days (or person-days) are absolute time measures, dependent on who’s doing the work, their experience, and availability.

Mixing the two defeats the purpose of story points — it turns relative estimation into time prediction, which Agile explicitly tries to avoid.



---

🧮 In practice (team-level use)

Some teams build an internal, empirical correlation, but only after several sprints:

For example, after a few iterations, you might notice that the team delivers around 30 points every 2 weeks.

If the team has 5 full-time members, you could infer roughly 3 points per person per week.
But this correlation is specific to that team and has no universal value.


> ⚠️ You should never say “1 point = 1 day” or “5 points = 3 days.” That’s considered a bad Agile practice.




---

💡 Summary

Concept	Type	Purpose

Story Points	Relative measure	Compare stories by effort
Man-days	Absolute measure	Plan capacity or workload
Direct correlation	❌ Not recommended	Breaks Agile estimation logic
Empirical internal correlation	✅ Acceptable (after observation)	Helps with velocity-based planning



